{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17799"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17799"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.15,0.8,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10513"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9927"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27728"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pons contains important centres that help control breathing patterns and respiratory rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the pontine respiratory centres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monitoring of blood oxygen levels","Generation of respiratory muscle tone","Detection of blood carbon dioxide levels","Modulation of respiratory rhythm and rate","Direct control of diaphragm contraction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emodulation of respiratory rhythm and rate\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the pontine respiratory centres. The pons contains both the pneumotaxic centre in its upper portion and the apneustic centre in its lower portion. These work together to fine-tune the basic rhythm generated by the medulla. The pneumotaxic centre limits inspiration and the apneustic centre prolongs and encourages inhalation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect control of diaphragm contraction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by motor neurons in the cervical spinal cord\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitoring of blood oxygen levels\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs primarily in the carotid and aortic bodies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration of respiratory muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E - This is maintained by motor neurons in the spinal cord\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of blood carbon dioxide levels\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs primarily in central chemoreceptors in the medulla\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pneumotaxic centre helps limit inspiration by inhibiting inspiratory neurons, while the apneustic centre promotes inspiration. Together they help establish normal breathing patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pontine respiratory centre contains both inspiratory and expiratory neurons that help regulate breathing rhythm.","The pneumotaxic centre in the upper pons modulates respiratory rate by inhibiting inspiration.","The apneustic centre in the lower pons promotes inspiration by stimulating the inspiratory neurons."],"references"